{{POV-check|date=November 2009}} {{POV-check|date=May 2014}}
The '''Nutritional Health Alliance''' is an industry [[lobby group]]<ref name = "sci">{{cite journal | first = Susan Katz| last = Miller| date =August 7, 1993 | title = The return of the medicine show| journal =New Scientist | url =https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg13918851.800-the-return-of-the-medicine-show-.html }}</ref><ref name = "phil">{{cite journal | first = Richard | last = Carelli| date =December 8, 1998 | title =FDA Rules on Dietary Supplements are Upheld | journal = Philadelphia Inquirer }} "a group of manufacturers, retailers"</ref><ref name = "NYT">{{cite journal | first = Lena| last =Williams | date =August 9, 1992 | title = F.D.A. Steps Up Effort to Control Vitamin Claims | journal =New York Times | url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE4DA1F38F93AA3575BC0A964958260&sec=health&spon=&pagewanted=2 }} "a new organization representing 25,000 vitamin makers and natural-food stores."</ref> which lobbies [[United States]] law makers to pass industry friendly health legislation.
The Nutritional Health Alliance was formed in 1992 by the [[supplement industry]] "to mount a forceful campaign to evade studies of their products." [[Gerald Kessler]], president of Nature's Plus, was the first head. Flyers were sent to health food stores with such titles as "The FDA wants to put you out of Business" and "Don't Let the FDA Take Your Vitamins Away" <ref name = "food">{{cite book | last = Hilts | first =Philip J. | year =2004 | title =Protecting America's Health | publisher =0807855820 | isbn =0-8078-5582-0 }} p. 285</ref>
The Nutritional Health Alliance is best known for its involvement in the ''Nutritional Health Alliance vs. Shalala'' case. In this case Nutritional Health Alliance argued to the second circuit that the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) mandating health claims on dietary supplements violated manufacturer's [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights.<ref name = "Advertising">{{cite book | last =Brody| first = Steven G. |author2=[[P. Cameron DeVore]] |author3=Bruce E. H. Johnson | year =2004 | title =Advertising and Commercial Speech: A First Amendment Guide| publisher = | isbn = 1-4024-0451-4 }}</ref>
